<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1437,150,1113]" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,399,258,285]" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">Taxonomic note.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stadie &amp; Fiebig &amp; Rajaei" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Stadie &amp; Fiebig &amp; Rajaei" baseAuthorityYear="2022" box="[409,580,259,285]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" genus="Hyrdria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="27" pageNumber="528" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="relicta" status="comb. n.">
<emphasis box="[409,580,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">Hyrdria relicta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[590,690,259,285]" pageId="27" pageNumber="528" rank="species">comb. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
shows all synapomorphies of the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[1165,1254,259,285]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" genus="Hyrdria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="27" pageNumber="528" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1165,1254,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">Hyrdria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
including wing venation and most importantly the presence of two areoles in forewing (only one areole in the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[1278,1429,295,321]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Rheumaptera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="528" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1278,1429,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">Rheumaptera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, see 
<figureCitation box="[193,256,331,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1962,1986]" captionTargetBox="[151,1431,275,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-83@2.[151,1435,270,1936]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Wing venation. Fig. 1a. Hydria cervinalis; Fig. 1b. Rheumaptera hastate. Pay attention to the presence of two areoles in forewing of Hydria vs. one areole in forewing of Rheumaptera." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5896495" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5896495/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
); presence of a large coremata on sternum A 
<quantity box="[753,793,331,357]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.032" pageId="27" pageNumber="528" unit="in" value="8.0">8 in</quantity>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stadie &amp; Fiebig &amp; Rajaei" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Stadie &amp; Fiebig &amp; Rajaei" baseAuthorityYear="2022" box="[799,904,331,357]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" genus="Hyrdria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="27" pageNumber="528" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="relicta">
<emphasis box="[799,904,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">H. relicta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(like other 
<taxonomicName box="[1031,1201,331,357]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Hydria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="528" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[1031,1110,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">Hydria</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
; very small coremata in 
<taxonomicName box="[179,330,367,393]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Rheumaptera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="528" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[179,330,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">Rheumaptera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Based on those morphological and further biological character combination (see below), herewith we transfer 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stadie &amp; Fiebig &amp; Rajaei" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Stadie &amp; Fiebig &amp; Rajaei" baseAuthorityYear="2022" box="[283,355,403,429]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" genus="Hyrdria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="27" pageNumber="528" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="relicta">
<emphasis box="[283,355,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">relicta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[505,584,403,429]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Hydria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="528" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[505,584,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">Hydria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="27" pageNumber="528" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1437,150,1113]" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,438,464]" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">Distribution</emphasis>
. The species is restricted to Mount 
<collectingCountry box="[746,819,439,465]" name="Kenya" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">Kenya</collectingCountry>
and the Aberdare range in central 
<collectingCountry box="[1207,1284,439,465]" name="Kenya" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">Kenya</collectingCountry>
. Host plant is 
<taxonomicName box="[151,325,475,501]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Berberidaceae" genus="Berberis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ranunculales" pageId="27" pageNumber="528" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="holstii">
<emphasis box="[151,325,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">Berberis holstii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the only 
<taxonomicName box="[438,534,475,501]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Berberidaceae" genus="Berberis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ranunculales" pageId="27" pageNumber="528" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[438,534,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">Berberis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-species that occur in tropical Africa. Though, the hostplant is rather widespread in East Africa (
<collectingCountry box="[322,421,511,537]" name="Ethiopia" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">Ethiopia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[433,509,511,537]" name="Kenya" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">Kenya</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[521,625,511,537]" name="Tanzania" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">Tanzania</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[636,731,511,537]" name="Somalia" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">Somalia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[743,833,511,537]" name="Uganda" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">Uganda</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[845,935,511,538]" name="Malawi" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">Malawi</collectingCountry>
), 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stadie &amp; Fiebig &amp; Rajaei" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Stadie &amp; Fiebig &amp; Rajaei" baseAuthorityYear="2022" box="[954,1061,511,537]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" genus="Hyrdria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="27" pageNumber="528" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="relicta">
<emphasis box="[954,1061,511,537]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">H. relicta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has not been recorded elsewhere yet.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1437,150,1113]" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,298,582,608]" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">Habitat.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stadie &amp; Fiebig &amp; Rajaei" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Stadie &amp; Fiebig &amp; Rajaei" baseAuthorityYear="2022" box="[307,477,583,609]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" genus="Hyrdria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="27" pageNumber="528" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="relicta">
<emphasis box="[307,477,583,609]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">Hyrdria relicta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
inhabits xeromontane steppes with fynbos elements (
<taxonomicName box="[1090,1165,583,608]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Proteaceae" genus="Protea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Proteales" pageId="27" pageNumber="528" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1090,1165,583,608]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">Protea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-species and 
<taxonomicName box="[1313,1426,583,608]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="27" pageNumber="528" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">
<emphasis box="[1313,1426,583,608]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">Ericaceae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and alpine moorland near or above the timber line between 
<quantity box="[805,970,619,645]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" metricValueMax="3.2" metricValueMin="2.8" pageId="27" pageNumber="528" unit="m" value="3000.0" valueMax="3200.0" valueMin="2800.0">
<geoCoordinate box="[805,869,619,645]" degrees="2,800" direction="north" orientation="latitude" pageId="27" pageNumber="528" precision="55" value="2.8">2,800</geoCoordinate>
<geoCoordinate box="[869,948,619,645]" degrees="3,200" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="27" pageNumber="528" precision="55" value="-3.2">–3,200</geoCoordinate>
m
</quantity>
. The hostplants occur at not too dry places in steep gorges or along swamp dips (
<figureCitation box="[573,704,655,681]" captionStart="FIGURES 78–84" captionStartId="24.[151,264,1754,1778]" captionTargetBox="[239,1349,182,1730]" captionTargetId="figure-28@24.[239,1349,181,1730]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURES 78–84. Photos of habitat, larva and adult specimens. Fig. 78. Hydria montivagata andalusica, Spain Sierra Nevada (reared) (photo. DIRK STaDIE); Fig. 79. L5-larva of Hydria montivagata andalusica, Spain Sierra Nevada ex larva (photo DIRK STaDIE); Fig. 80. Habitat of Hydria relicta, a vegetation with a steppic character near the timber line, in fore ground xeromontane steppe with Protea-species and several Ericaceae (montane Fynbos elements) in the background trees of Hagenia abyssinica and Juniperus procera at Rutundu fishing lodge (Mount Kenya) at 3,100m (photo PHILIPP STaDIE, RaLF FIEbIG); Figs 81–83. Habitat of Hydria relicta, area around Rutundu fishing lodge (montane Fynbos elements) Mount Kenya (photo PHILIPP STaDIE, RaLF FIEbIG); Fig. 84. Host plant Berberis holstii of Hydria relicta near Rutundu fishing lodge at Mount Kenya (photo Dirk Stadie)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5896523" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5896523/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">Figs 80–84</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1437,150,1113]" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,329,691,717]" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">Phenology.</emphasis>
The sparse material originates from April, September and October. However, the habitats where this species occurs have day climate conditions without stronger changes around the year. Therefore, we suggest a multivoltine development, with 5–6 generations per year. This hypothesis is supported by rearing under laboratory conditions (pers. observation of the senior author).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="27" pageNumber="528" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1437,150,1113]" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,295,834,860]" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">Biology.</emphasis>
The species was reared under laboratory conditions on 
<taxonomicName box="[960,1182,835,861]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Berberidaceae" genus="Berberis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ranunculales" pageId="27" pageNumber="528" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="communis">
<emphasis box="[960,1182,835,861]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">Berberis communis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The life cycle of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stadie &amp; Fiebig &amp; Rajaei" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Stadie &amp; Fiebig &amp; Rajaei" baseAuthorityYear="2022" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" genus="Hyrdria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="27" pageNumber="528" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="relicta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">H. relicta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is highly similar to other 
<taxonomicName box="[511,679,871,897]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Hydria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="528" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[511,590,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">Hydria</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
of the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Scopoli" baseAuthorityYear="1763" box="[756,866,871,897]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Hydria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="528" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cervinalis">
<emphasis box="[756,866,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">cervinalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
- and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Duponchel" baseAuthorityYear="1830" box="[930,1070,871,896]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Hydria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="528" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="montivagata">
<emphasis box="[930,1070,871,896]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">montivagata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-group, namely behaviour, larval morphology and hostplant (all of them feeding on 
<taxonomicName box="[712,898,907,934]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Berberidaceae" genus="Berberis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ranunculales" pageId="27" pageNumber="528" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[712,808,907,933]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">Berberis</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
) (pers. observation of the senior author). Larvae of 
<taxonomicName box="[186,429,943,969]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Rheumaptera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="528" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[186,337,943,969]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">Rheumaptera</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
as much as known are broad oligophagous on 
<taxonomicName box="[994,1112,943,969]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Salicaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="27" pageNumber="528" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Salicaceae</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[1133,1189,943,969]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Salicaceae" genus="Salix" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="27" pageNumber="528" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1133,1189,943,969]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">Salix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[1208,1300,943,969]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Salicaceae" genus="Populus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="27" pageNumber="528" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1208,1300,943,969]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">Populus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), 
<taxonomicName box="[1327,1436,943,969]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="27" pageNumber="528" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Ericaceae</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[161,278,979,1004]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" genus="Vaccinium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="27" pageNumber="528" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[161,278,979,1004]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">Vaccinium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), 
<taxonomicName authorityName="S.F.Gray" authorityYear="1822" box="[300,423,979,1005]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Betulaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="27" pageNumber="528" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Betulaceae</taxonomicName>
and others and none of them feeding on 
<taxonomicName box="[881,1073,979,1005]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Berberidaceae" genus="Berberis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ranunculales" pageId="27" pageNumber="528" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[881,977,979,1005]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">Berberis</emphasis>
species.
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1437,150,1113]" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">
Unfortunately, most of the larvae of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stadie &amp; Fiebig &amp; Rajaei" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Stadie &amp; Fiebig &amp; Rajaei" baseAuthorityYear="1953" box="[605,763,1015,1041]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Hydria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="528" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="relicta">
<emphasis box="[605,763,1015,1041]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="528">Hydria relicta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were died during the expedition and after few ecdysis. Only 
<specimenCount box="[151,270,1051,1077]" pageId="27" pageNumber="528" type="larva">two larvae</specimenCount>
survived and reached L5. After pupation one normal sized female was hatching. The pupal stage lasts for three weeks.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
